---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import HeroSection from '../components/HeroSection.astro';
import ChartSection from '../components/ChartSection.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import SkillFilters from '../components/SkillFilters';
import PopulationChart from '../components/PopulationChart';
import CategoryTrendChart from '../components/CategoryTrendChart';
import ComplexityChart from '../components/ComplexityChart';
---
<BaseLayout>
  <HeroSection />

  <!-- Scale explanation -->
  <section id="reading-the-scale" style="padding:3.5rem 2rem 0;max-width:1400px;margin:0 auto;">
    <div style="max-width:65ch;margin:0 auto;">
      <h2 style="
        font-family:'Raleway','Arial Black',sans-serif;
        font-size:clamp(1.5rem,4vw,2.2rem);
        font-weight:800;
        letter-spacing:-0.02em;
        color:#F2F0E5;
        margin-bottom:0.35rem;
      ">Reading the Scale</h2>
      <p style="color:#64748b;margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
        All charts use a 0–10 scale calibrated to average expectations for a <strong style="color:#F2F0E5;">senior developer</strong> role.
      </p>
      <dl style="display:grid;gap:0.25rem;color:#94a3b8;font-size:1rem;line-height:1.25;">
        <div style="display:flex;gap:0.5rem;">
          <dt style="color:#FFCD68;font-weight:700;font-size:1rem;min-width:1.5rem;text-align:right;">0</dt>
          <dd><strong style="color:#F2F0E5;">Not on the radar.</strong> The skill didn't exist yet or nobody considered it relevant.</dd>
        </div>
        <div style="display:flex;gap:0.5rem;">
          <dt style="color:#FFCD68;font-weight:700;font-size:1rem;min-width:1.5rem;text-align:right;">5</dt>
          <dd><strong style="color:#F2F0E5;">Helps you get the job.</strong> Having it sets you apart, but not having it won't disqualify you.</dd>
        </div>
        <div style="display:flex;gap:0.5rem;">
          <dt style="color:#FFCD68;font-weight:700;font-size:1rem;min-width:1.5rem;text-align:right;">8</dt>
          <dd><strong style="color:#F2F0E5;">Not having it keeps you out.</strong> Most teams treat this as a hard requirement for senior candidates.</dd>
        </div>
        <div style="display:flex;gap:0.5rem;">
          <dt style="color:#FFCD68;font-weight:700;font-size:1rem;min-width:1.5rem;text-align:right;">10</dt>
          <dd><strong style="color:#F2F0E5;">Not even considered a candidate without it.</strong> The skill is so fundamental it's assumed, not tested.</dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>

  <ChartSection
    id="category-trends"
    title="Skill Radar — Then vs Now"
    subtitle="What skills did the industry expect from senior developers — and how did that change over time? It used to be simple: know your hardware and write good code. Over the decades the shape pulled outward as architecture, product sense, teamwork, and UX became just as important. Hardware and raw coding shrank while AI appeared out of nowhere. The tight sliver became a full polygon — today, being senior means being good at almost everything."
  >
    <CategoryTrendChart client:only="react" />
  </ChartSection>

  <ChartSection
    id="skills-timeline"
    title="Senior Developer Skills Timeline"
    subtitle="Skill expectations · 1970–2026 · Mainstream software development"
  >
    <SkillFilters client:only="react" />
  </ChartSection>

  <ChartSection
    id="population"
    title="Developer Population"
    subtitle="Estimated worldwide software developers · 1970–2026 · millions"
  >
    <PopulationChart client:only="react" />
  </ChartSection>

  <ChartSection
    id="complexity"
    title="Software Complexity Growth"
    subtitle="Key complexity indicators · 1970–2026"
  >
    <ComplexityChart client:only="react" />

    <div class="complexity-metrics">
      <div class="complexity-metric">
        <h3><span class="metric-dot" style="background:#e879f9;"></span>Decision Points incl. Dependencies</h3>
        <p>
          Every <code>if</code>, loop, and pattern-match in your project is a decision point — a place where
          behavior can diverge and a bug can hide. Modern applications ship with thousands of transitive
          dependencies, each adding their own branching logic. This metric estimates the total number of
          decision points across a project and its dependency tree. It's the single best proxy for how
          much behavior a senior developer is implicitly responsible for when they hit "deploy".
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="complexity-metric">
        <h3><span class="metric-dot" style="background:#60a5fa;"></span>Linux Kernel Lines of Code</h3>
        <p>
          The Linux kernel is the most widely deployed piece of software on earth — it runs phones,
          servers, cars, and satellites. Its growth is a reliable thermometer for how complex the
          underlying platform has become. When the kernel doubles, drivers, syscalls, and edge cases
          double with it, and every layer built on top inherits that complexity.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="complexity-metric">
        <h3><span class="metric-dot" style="background:#4ade80;"></span>npm Packages</h3>
        <p>
          npm is the world's largest package registry and a proxy for ecosystem fragmentation.
          More packages means more choices for every task, more transitive dependencies to audit, and
          more surface area for supply-chain attacks. A senior developer in 2010 might have evaluated
          a handful of libraries; today they inherit hundreds the moment they scaffold a project.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="complexity-metric">
        <h3><span class="metric-dot" style="background:#f87171;"></span>CVEs per Year</h3>
        <p>
          The number of publicly disclosed vulnerabilities each year reflects the security burden on
          every team. More CVEs means more patches to apply, more dependency upgrades to evaluate,
          and more time spent on security reviews instead of features. It's a direct measure of the
          "maintenance tax" that complexity imposes.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="complexity-metric">
        <h3><span class="metric-dot" style="background:#fbbf24;"></span>Technologies in a Typical Stack</h3>
        <p>
          In 1970, a senior developer needed to know an editor and a language. Today a single
          full-stack project may touch a framework, a bundler, a type system, a CSS preprocessor,
          a test runner, a CI pipeline, a container runtime, an orchestrator, a cloud provider, and
          a dozen SaaS integrations. This metric estimates the number of distinct technologies a
          senior developer is expected to navigate — and it explains why "just learning the language"
          stopped being enough decades ago.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </ChartSection>

  <style>
    .complexity-metrics {
      display: grid;
      gap: 1.5rem;
      margin-top: 2rem;
      padding-top: 1.5rem;
      border-top: 1px solid #3a3a3a;
    }
    .complexity-metric h3 {
      font-family: 'Raleway', 'Arial Black', sans-serif;
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      color: #F2F0E5;
      margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: 0.5rem;
    }
    .metric-dot {
      display: inline-block;
      width: 10px;
      height: 10px;
      border-radius: 50%;
      flex-shrink: 0;
    }
    .complexity-metric p {
      color: #94a3b8;
      line-height: 1.7;
      font-size: 0.95rem;
    }
    .complexity-metric code {
      color: #F2F0E5;
      font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
      font-size: 0.88em;
    }
  </style>

  <!-- About / Methodology -->
  <section style="padding:3.5rem 2rem;max-width:800px;margin:0 auto;">
    <h2 style="
      font-family:'Raleway','Arial Black',sans-serif;
      font-size:1.8rem;
      font-weight:800;
      letter-spacing:-0.02em;
      color:#F2F0E5;
      margin-bottom:1rem;
    ">About & Methodology</h2>

    <div style="color:#94a3b8;line-height:1.8;font-size:0.97rem;">
      <p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
        All skill values follow a <strong style="color:#F2F0E5;">logistic S-curve model</strong> — skills emerge slowly,
        accelerate through adoption, then plateau at market saturation. The 0–10 scale represents market expectation,
        not personal skill level: <strong style="color:#F2F0E5;">0</strong> = not on the radar,
        <strong style="color:#F2F0E5;">5</strong> = useful, not required,
        <strong style="color:#F2F0E5;">8</strong> = required,
        <strong style="color:#F2F0E5;">10</strong> = expectation baseline.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
        Data is heuristic — not absolute truth. Validated against Stack Overflow Developer Surveys,
        JetBrains Developer Ecosystem Reports, DORA State of DevOps, CNCF Annual Surveys, and Martin Fowler's writing.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is an open community resource.
        Contributions, corrections, and new skill proposals are welcome via GitHub.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
